<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<FLOW VERSION="3.0" CLEANUP="true">
  <COMMENT> splitIF - system service for splitting an inbound document into equivalent child documents </COMMENT>

  <!-- nodes -->

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT> splitIFjson - system service for splitting an inbound JSON document into equivalent child documents - splits content1 </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>  This service will split a grouped JSON document (stored as content1) into a series of individual documents based on the json being </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   formatted as a proper json array at the highest level.  This means that the JSON must contain the following: </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>            {  &#34;name&#34; : [                                 </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   where &#34;name&#34; is the name of the array of documents that follow.   Note that the array does not have to explicitly </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   be called &#34;name&#34;, rather it must be a simple array name that has no embedded spaces.  See the first DEBUG sample below for </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   an example of how this looks.   Each element of the main array must contain one or more properly structured JSON documents. </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   This service will create one CHILD transaction for each sub-document in the original JSON array and then end the entire workflow </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   immediately.  If no array is found, then no CHILD transactions are created and this service ends normally, meaning </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   the workflow will continue.  This generally means we are in a CHILD transaction already.  On the other hand, if an array *is* found, </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   but the array is *empty*, then no child transactions will be created and the workflow will be terminated quietly.  This can happen </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>   if the parent has 0 documents in its array. See the fourth DEBUG sample below.  </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>  It is assumed, of course, that the original array contains documents that are all identical in format.  This service is NOT suitable </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>  for an array of dissimilar documents. </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT>     2/5/25 - modified to support OPT_SPLIT_CONTENT </COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

<SEQUENCE TIMEOUT="" EXIT-ON="FAILURE">
  <COMMENT></COMMENT>
</SEQUENCE>

